# {{ service_name }}-client

Typed TypeScript gRPC client for the `{{ service_name }}` service.

## Quick start

```sh
npm install
npm run gen      # codegen from ../proto/
npm run build    # tsc → dist/
```

## Node usage (`@grpc/grpc-js`)

```ts
import * as grpc from "@grpc/grpc-js";
import { {{ ServiceCamel }}Client, HelloRequest, AuthCtx } from "{{ service_name }}-client";

const client = new {{ ServiceCamel }}Client(
  "{{ service_name }}:50051",
  grpc.credentials.createInsecure(),
);

const metadata = new grpc.Metadata();
AuthCtx.fromBearer(myToken).propagate(metadata);

client.sayHello({ name: "world" }, metadata, (err, reply) => {
  if (err) throw err;
  console.log(reply.message);
});
```

## Browser usage (`grpc-web`)

```sh
npm install grpc-web      # explicit (optional peer dep)
```

```ts
import { {{ ServiceCamel }}Client, HelloRequest, AuthCtx } from "{{ service_name }}-client";

// Browser-side requires an Envoy / Nginx grpc-web proxy in front of
// the service. The endpoint here points at the proxy, not directly
// at the gRPC port.
const client = new {{ ServiceCamel }}Client("http://envoy-proxy/", null);

const metadata: Record<string, string> = {};
AuthCtx.fromBearer(myToken).propagate(metadata);

client.sayHello(new HelloRequest({ name: "world" }), metadata)
  .then((reply) => console.log(reply.getMessage()));
```

## Two transports, one wire format

Both transports speak the same proto. The two-codepath cost lives only
inside this client crate; service authors and peers see one consistent
API. Cilium mesh handles east-west traffic between services; Envoy
handles browser-to-mesh translation.

## Shared client-side primitives

`AuthCtx`, `RetryPolicy`, `CircuitBreaker` are intentionally shaped to
match the Rust (`tonin-client`) and Python (`tonin_client`)
equivalents — same field names, same defaults. A request authorized
in a Python service stays authorized when relayed by a TS BFF.
